      <PrimaryExemptPurposeTxt>Our mission is to protect Norwalks irreplaceable historic buildings and neighborhoods landscapes and streetscapes by raising awareness and taking appropriate action when necessary. We fulfill this mission through advocacy and education including public events like tours and workshops. We are a voice for preservation and an information resource for homeowners residents businesses and developers as well as city state and national organizations and government agencies.</PrimaryExemptPurposeTxt>
      <ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
        <DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>Educational program focused on historic preservation. Our "Houses of Change" tour on October 13 2024 explored architectural adaptation and change in 19th-century residential homes. Restorations and renovations can and should be done with sensitivity to traditional building methods and materials. Helping you to "get your house right" is part of our mission. 48 people attended the tour. 60 people attended the reception afterwards. You can learn more and see photos on our web site under Current News.</DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>
        <GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>0</GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>
        <ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>5120</ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>
      </ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
      <ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
        <DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>As a lead-in to our Houses of Change tour see above on September 22 we presented a keynote lecture "Buildings of Change," by Christopher Wigren a prominent architectural historian of Connecticut. 28 people attended the lecture at the Norwalk Public Library free and open to the public. You can learn more and see photos on our web site under Current News.</DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>
        <GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>0</GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>
        <ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>310</ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>
      </ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
      <ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
        <DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>Community-building exercise focused on historic preservation and urban renewal related to our organizational mission. Our 2024 Janes Walk program featured a walking tour of South Norwalks historic districts focused on two major projects in this urban space the replacement of the railroad bridge and two historic buildings that will be demolished to make way for a hotel project. We talked with residents in front of their homes and with business owners in their establishments. More than 20 people attended. This was a free event with NPT leadership donating their time and expertise. You can learn more and see photos on our web site under Current News.</DescriptionProgramSrvcAccomTxt>
        <GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>0</GrantsAndAllocationsAmt>
        <ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>0</ProgramServiceExpensesAmt>
      </ProgramSrvcAccomplishmentGrp>
