        <ExplanationTxt>| PartandLinenumber:,Explanation:| Part2SectionBLine1d,NPT sent two different email call-to-action campaigns with subsequent follow-up newsletters updates and reminders. The first issue was our opposition to the demolition of two historic buildings on South Main Street in South Norwalk. We sent three dedicated emails two Letters from the President one Call to Action asking the public the write letters to the State Historic Preservation Office opposing the demolitions. NPT also submitted a letter in opposition. See the Current News section of our web site for more about the response to this effort and its outcome. The second issue was Connecticut House Bill 5433 which would have allowed property developers to pay to bypass the State Historic Preservation Offices review process. We sent a Call to Action email in March with subsequent updates in our newsletters. The bill passed but the provision that we opposed was removed.| Part2SectionBLine1e,See the Current News section of our web site for an article we published there providing details of our opposition to the South Main Street demolitions and the hotel project.| Part2SectionBLine1g,In addition to our email campaigns newsletters and web site publications our leadership also had direct contact by email and by phone with the State Historic Preservation Office about the South Main Street buildings. In addition NPT signed a joint letter with three other historic-preservation organizations sent to the Connecticut legislative leadership President Pro Tempore Senate Majority Leader Speaker of the House House Majority Leader about House Bill 5433.|</ExplanationTxt>
